00:11:49.140 --> 00:11:55.800
Not so much in terms of size, you know, in terms of number of machines or all of that, but more in terms of mindset and orientation.

00:11:55.800 --> 00:12:03.940
I want to see a focus on building things well, automating where possible, and having a long-term view of the systems you put in place.

00:12:03.940 --> 00:12:08.360
And I look for a time that you've applied productive laziness to solve a problem.

00:12:10.520 --> 00:12:20.060
So, the most important fundamental skills I look for are closely related to experience, environmental fluidity, and personal learning ability.

00:12:20.060 --> 00:12:21.500
Now, what do those mean?

00:12:21.500 --> 00:12:27.260
So, as for environmental fluidity, well, specifically, PayPal uses a lot of Linux.

00:12:27.260 --> 00:12:34.220
So, I look for candidates that can demonstrate familiarity at the console, interacting with the operating system.

00:12:34.220 --> 00:12:40.500
While I don't usually give candidates complex, algorithmic questions on the spot during interviews,

00:12:40.500 --> 00:12:46.200
I do log them into PayPal's test servers and have them do a little bit of basic debugging.

00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:51.780
For the experienced people, you can almost feel them relaxing into a familiar environment.

00:12:51.780 --> 00:12:57.340
For the inexperienced, the terminal can be an aptly named dark and scary place.

00:12:57.340 --> 00:13:02.500
Either way, the command line is a foundational technology critical to enterprise work,

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:05.320
and I really feel like it's not going away anytime soon.

00:13:05.620 --> 00:13:13.400
So, lack of command line comfort is a big yellow flag, especially when Linux is so widespread and easy to experiment with on your own.

00:13:13.400 --> 00:13:17.240
The other characteristic I look for is learning ability.

00:13:17.240 --> 00:13:23.400
The skills to read and research naturally, absorbing and arranging information automatically,

00:13:23.920 --> 00:13:29.520
because I've been burned once or twice by talented people who were honestly just too lazy to read the docs,

00:13:29.520 --> 00:13:31.780
or too intimidated to read the source code.

00:13:31.780 --> 00:13:36.180
You don't have to do it in big gulps, but you do need to do it consistently.

00:13:36.180 --> 00:13:39.740
So, I usually look at what candidates have done to learn lately,

00:13:39.740 --> 00:13:43.060
like the sources they've been consulting and so forth.

00:13:43.700 --> 00:13:48.860
So, for instance, I'll say, show me some source code you've written and what you learned during that process.

00:13:48.860 --> 00:13:54.100
Or, tell me about a project that sounds much simpler than it actually was.

00:13:54.100 --> 00:13:57.840
You know, I might ask, what sites taught you the web?

00:13:57.840 --> 00:14:00.620
Or, have you seen any noteworthy source code lately?

00:14:00.620 --> 00:14:02.960
Have you read any good books?

00:14:03.820 --> 00:14:07.060
On the other hand, I watch out for Hacker News-y types.

00:14:07.060 --> 00:14:12.320
My projects have topped HN several times in the last couple years, and some lurking is fine,

00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:19.340
but I want someone ready to outgrow that consumption and commodification of the creative work that is software

00:14:19.340 --> 00:14:23.320
that gets interleaved with the press releases on Hacker News.

00:14:23.320 --> 00:14:29.580
Someone who's ready to dedicate time to actually create the sorts of things that others will upvote.

00:14:31.220 --> 00:14:38.540
I think the most important piece of experience is how they approach problems and break it down

00:14:38.540 --> 00:14:43.380
and turn something that may have seemed otherwise impossible or very difficult,

00:14:43.380 --> 00:14:46.160
how they broke that down to smaller, more manageable pieces.

00:14:46.160 --> 00:14:53.700
After all, coding is about problem solving, and we are building recipes to automate tasks,

00:14:53.700 --> 00:14:57.980
to automate things, to make an ecosystem that can work in harmony.

00:14:57.980 --> 00:15:03.980
So when a candidate comes in and they talk about problems that they've solved and how they went about doing it,

00:15:03.980 --> 00:15:07.760
really I'm trying to see what was the original problem,

00:15:07.760 --> 00:15:12.600
what were the ways they went about trying to solve the problem, what worked and what didn't,

00:15:12.600 --> 00:15:14.680
and also, you know, where's the passion?

00:15:14.680 --> 00:15:15.640
What really drives them?

00:15:15.640 --> 00:15:20.260
I think it's really important to have people who are excited about what they do

00:15:20.260 --> 00:15:25.700
and are okay to, they're okay with things failing because at the end of the day,

00:15:25.700 --> 00:15:27.820
you're going to try things and it might not work,

00:15:27.820 --> 00:15:33.360
but you need to have the ability to then sit down, reflect, understand what went wrong,

00:15:33.360 --> 00:15:36.060
and move forward to iterate and try something else.

00:15:36.060 --> 00:15:40.300
Demonstrate problem solving, I definitely think is the most important piece of experience.

00:15:42.620 --> 00:15:45.780
I think there are two pieces, important pieces.

00:15:45.780 --> 00:15:50.360
The first one is responsibility and the second one is maturity.

00:15:50.360 --> 00:15:51.540
Why?

00:15:51.540 --> 00:15:55.140
From my point of view and from my experience,

00:15:55.140 --> 00:15:58.620
usually people who actually have never worked before,

00:15:58.620 --> 00:15:59.980
for example, students,

00:15:59.980 --> 00:16:03.220
they don't lack technical skills,

00:16:03.220 --> 00:16:05.080
they lack social skills.

00:16:05.620 --> 00:16:07.660
And social skills are crucial.

00:16:07.660 --> 00:16:10.220
They lack of communicability.

00:16:10.220 --> 00:16:13.900
They lack of responsibility, maturity.

00:16:13.900 --> 00:16:21.260
Because majority of people think that programmers and programming in particular isn't antisocial.

00:16:21.260 --> 00:16:27.020
And programmers are people who actually are staring at the screens all day long

00:16:27.020 --> 00:16:32.620
and writing some magical code and doing something magical.

00:16:33.360 --> 00:16:37.480
But I think that programming is a social skill as well.

00:16:37.480 --> 00:16:39.660
Because in order to create something,

00:16:39.660 --> 00:16:42.740
in order to create something valuable,

00:16:42.740 --> 00:16:45.840
you have to communicate with many people.

00:16:45.840 --> 00:16:47.900
You have to communicate with managers.

00:16:47.900 --> 00:16:51.000
You have to communicate with your team members.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:53.620
You should be a good team player.

00:16:53.620 --> 00:16:56.380
You should communicate with customers.

00:16:56.380 --> 00:17:01.400
Also, you should communicate with the end users of your products

00:17:01.400 --> 00:17:03.100
in order to get feedback.

00:17:03.100 --> 00:17:05.420
You should be responsible for everything.

00:17:05.420 --> 00:17:07.180
You should write effectively.

00:17:07.180 --> 00:17:12.160
You should express your thoughts concisely in a written form.

00:17:12.160 --> 00:17:16.320
I think writing is also a very crucial skill for programmers.

00:17:16.320 --> 00:17:19.660
I mean, not writing code, but writing articles,

00:17:19.660 --> 00:17:22.280
express your thoughts and stuff like that.

00:17:22.280 --> 00:17:26.220
And if a person is responsible and mature,

00:17:26.220 --> 00:17:28.860
it is a great pleasure to work with him.

00:17:28.860 --> 00:17:37.040
We particularly look for experiences where a developer has taken a task

00:17:37.040 --> 00:17:40.440
and researched community packages that can be imported

00:17:40.440 --> 00:17:46.180
in order to complete the objective faster than if they were to write vanilla code

00:17:46.180 --> 00:17:47.660
in place of that.

00:17:47.840 --> 00:17:54.820
The reality of today's code economy with open source technologies is that codes and packages

00:17:54.820 --> 00:17:59.200
likely have already been written to assist in completing particular tasks.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:04.980
And that means mostly the challenge becomes then kind of assembling those components together

00:18:04.980 --> 00:18:08.960
with some of your own custom development to solve the particular problem.

00:18:10.960 --> 00:18:15.280
I don't often encourage writing code without consulting existing packages.

00:18:15.280 --> 00:18:23.240
We use packages such as requests and Flask, for instance, quite heavily.

00:18:23.240 --> 00:18:27.880
It's just less necessary than when Python was first developed.

00:18:28.880 --> 00:18:35.220
We also require that developers know how to set up a virtual environment, virtually in V, for instance,

00:18:35.220 --> 00:18:38.880
in order to create isolation of their package needs,

00:18:38.880 --> 00:18:43.620
which can then further be built onto continuous deployment practices.

00:18:43.620 --> 00:18:50.960
From a code centric perspective, we look for things such as good practices around exception handling,

00:18:50.960 --> 00:18:56.280
logging, security best practices in your code, those types of things.

00:18:56.700 --> 00:19:02.200
Any code written must follow good standards around those types of things.

00:19:02.200 --> 00:19:08.300
Unexpected data formats, bad JSON structures, all those types of things.

00:19:08.300 --> 00:19:10.820
So those are critical to what we review.

00:19:10.820 --> 00:19:21.660
The most important experience I always look for in a candidate is not knowledge with a particular piece of technology,

00:19:21.880 --> 00:19:28.040
but curiosity and demonstrating that they are actually interested in programming.

00:19:28.040 --> 00:19:32.080
