00:24:34.020 --> 00:24:37.780
We have different types of learning, be it formal or non.

00:24:37.780 --> 00:24:41.680
But what I think I get most excited about is more side projects.

00:24:41.680 --> 00:24:44.920
Maybe someone started on something that isn't within their day-to-day role,

00:24:45.240 --> 00:24:46.840
and they got really excited about it.

00:24:46.840 --> 00:24:48.800
And then they went out there and they wanted to learn more.

00:24:48.800 --> 00:24:58.140
So does someone have a side project like they were curious perhaps about how they could take a problem that maybe perhaps all developers have,

00:24:58.140 --> 00:24:59.560
which is, you know, writing good documentation.

00:24:59.560 --> 00:25:05.240
You know, do they recognize a need that it's somewhat painful and or an afterthought to write documentation?

00:25:05.240 --> 00:25:08.380
And then they're like, okay, how can I write a tool that will make this better?

00:25:08.380 --> 00:25:11.020
And then they turn that into a side project.

00:25:11.020 --> 00:25:23.580
Or maybe they're curious about machine learning and they've started taking a Coursera class and they're taking a project or a algorithm into their own and applying it to a project.

00:25:23.580 --> 00:25:31.400
I think ways that we learn, you know, you are passionate about exploring and learning outside and creating your own projects,

00:25:31.400 --> 00:25:37.560
that really demonstrates initiative and really demonstrates a curiosity that I think is fundamental for coding.

00:25:37.560 --> 00:25:40.720
So side projects are really exciting to me.

00:25:40.720 --> 00:25:43.540
And also show the creativity of a developer.

00:25:43.540 --> 00:25:47.920
And then also open source contributions are pretty exciting as well.

00:25:47.920 --> 00:25:53.020
Particularly if someone has used a tool a lot and they start recognizing the holes or problems.

00:25:53.020 --> 00:26:02.820
Or even if they're saying, the way I learned how to use a project is I went through and started following bugs and started adding documentation to an open source project.

00:26:02.820 --> 00:26:11.060
Adding documentation to a project might seem like a small and insignificant thing, but actually can be quite useful and important.

00:26:11.060 --> 00:26:21.140
So really, you know, side projects, they may seem to be terribly overwhelming or large, but there's other ways you can go about doing it, finding a favorite tool and finding ways to contribute.

00:26:21.140 --> 00:26:27.420
So I think those are two ways that people can demonstrate things that they've worked on.

