Do they act as a mentor?

00:26:42.580 --> 00:26:49.460
The Chicago Python user group has a mentoring program, which I've really not heard many user groups doing.

00:26:49.780 --> 00:26:57.760
So it's exciting to see someone say they have a love for something and they're ready to give back, be it as a mentor or maybe even as a mentee, are they participating in one?

00:26:57.760 --> 00:27:01.380
Giving talks at local user groups, giving talks at conferences.

00:27:01.380 --> 00:27:12.920
I think all those things are very interesting as well because it's going to show how they'll create community within your work environment and how they'll be contributing to the procurement of knowledge in days to come.

00:27:13.020 --> 00:27:21.100
It's important to have people who are looking to add to the conversation rather than just participating in the conversation as it exists.

00:27:21.100 --> 00:27:25.300
I think that everything matters.

00:27:25.300 --> 00:27:27.080
The more, the better.

00:27:27.080 --> 00:27:40.060
Because from my point of view and my experience hiring developers in Kazakhstan, usually people who are applying for their first job don't have anything to present.

00:27:40.960 --> 00:27:45.020
That's why it is very, very difficult to make right decision based on this.

00:27:45.020 --> 00:27:47.960
It starts looks like a Russian roulette.

00:27:47.960 --> 00:27:53.360
You start to rely on your intuition, which is not the good decision-making technique.

00:27:53.360 --> 00:28:00.320
And I would say that it is better to make mistake and not hire a good person rather than hire a wrong person.

00:28:01.060 --> 00:28:10.980
And that's why if a no previous job experience candidate shows his interest in terms of open source contributions, site projects, etc.

00:28:10.980 --> 00:28:13.800
It is definitely a big plus for him.

00:28:13.800 --> 00:28:18.760
And I would highly recommend to explore a wide range of open source projects.

00:28:19.080 --> 00:28:39.780
It is not the only best way to explore other programming code, but also opportunity to share your code and get feedback from more experienced developers, which is very important in real projects, where the majority of your time you spend with working with other experienced developers and working with the legacy code.

00:28:40.080 --> 00:28:51.080
So take a look at Django, take a look at Flask, requests, SQLAlchemy, and tons of excellent open source projects and start exploring and contributing to them.

