Question number four, degrees.

00:34:24.300 --> 00:34:26.780
So this is an interesting question.

00:34:26.780 --> 00:34:31.320
Which one do I value more, or which one does the company value more?

00:34:31.320 --> 00:34:35.060
Because management marketability really comes into it with large companies.

00:34:35.060 --> 00:34:41.160
Of the three hires I truly consider my star hires, none of them had a CS degree.

00:34:41.160 --> 00:34:46.500
One was electrical engineering, the other was math, and the final one was comparative literature.

00:34:47.360 --> 00:34:56.320
The things they all had in common, though, was just a voracious reading habit and extensive hours spent in some Python or POSIX environment.

00:34:56.320 --> 00:35:00.580
Computer science degrees aren't really necessary for the majority of enterprise work.

00:35:00.580 --> 00:35:06.480
Like I said before, environmental fluidity and willingness to read docs are far more important.

00:35:06.480 --> 00:35:12.440
A couple of CS classes will get you some useful vocabulary and teach you time complexity, though.

00:35:13.020 --> 00:35:19.960
As for the concept of a degree in general, if you want to work at a big company, it's a lot easier to get in with a bachelor's.

00:35:19.960 --> 00:35:22.080
You don't need much more than that.

00:35:22.080 --> 00:35:31.540
The right two years of experience can go a long way in terms of skills development, but in terms of management marketability, no degree raises a lot of eyebrows in those cases.

00:35:31.920 --> 00:35:41.260
So, in short, for enterprise software, my observation is that a computer science degree is about as good as a non-CS degree plus two years of experience,

00:35:41.260 --> 00:35:46.660
which is about as good as no degree plus four to five years of experience at least.

00:35:46.660 --> 00:35:55.080
