00:35:55.800 --> 00:35:59.160
Basically, everything is about how you approach your assignments in free time.

00:35:59.160 --> 00:36:03.260
If you push beyond the requirements, you will learn much more.

00:36:03.260 --> 00:36:07.160
So, if you're in school, take an operating systems class.

00:36:07.160 --> 00:36:09.020
Take a networking class.

00:36:09.020 --> 00:36:10.900
Maybe take a crypto class.

00:36:10.900 --> 00:36:13.960
You'll learn almost as much running a shared server in your dorm.

00:36:13.960 --> 00:36:18.900
Now, both of those are different types of knowledge, so consider doing both.

00:36:19.240 --> 00:36:26.420
If you're not in school, Coursera and other options are far better than nothing, and I'd like to hear about those experiences in interviews.

00:36:26.420 --> 00:36:35.700
So, for candidates that have computer science degrees and those who don't, I don't actually have a preference of one over the other.

00:36:35.960 --> 00:36:41.820
I think that something that's unique or maybe interesting about Sprout, we are a startup.

00:36:41.820 --> 00:36:42.720
We're about five years.

00:36:42.720 --> 00:36:44.720
We're in our fifth year here in Chicago.

00:36:44.720 --> 00:36:49.180
I think startups are interesting spaces because you get people with a broader background.

00:36:49.180 --> 00:36:51.180
At least that's been my experience.

00:36:51.180 --> 00:36:57.640
And when you have people who come from different backgrounds, you know, maybe someone who was both technical and was a lawyer.

00:36:57.880 --> 00:37:03.600
Or maybe someone came from a PhD that wasn't in computer science and went into programming.

00:37:03.600 --> 00:37:06.640
Or maybe someone who was a musician and came into that.

00:37:06.640 --> 00:37:11.260
Speaking of which, these are all examples of people I know and work with that have these types of backgrounds.

00:37:11.260 --> 00:37:17.740
These are some of the most exciting people to work with because their ways of breaking and approaching problems, they come from different vantage points.

00:37:18.580 --> 00:37:25.640
So, definitely, I think having the ability to speak about fundamentals is somewhat non-negotiable.

00:37:25.640 --> 00:37:31.840
You need to understand how to talk about the complexity of an algorithm and understand its performance.

00:37:31.840 --> 00:37:33.200
So, big O is important.

00:37:33.200 --> 00:37:38.800
You need to understand different types of data structures and what is applicable in an appropriate situation.

00:37:38.800 --> 00:37:48.480
And I think for people who don't have formal education, these are the type of things that you can learn over time or you can take the initiative to learn on your own.

00:37:48.480 --> 00:37:56.040
So, while a computer science degree is definitely a good indicator of someone's skill set, it's not the end all.

00:37:56.040 --> 00:38:00.380
You're looking for a nice combination of things.

00:38:00.380 --> 00:38:06.660
So, for people who don't have formal education, I think what's important is that they're continuing in their learning and how is it they're doing it.

00:38:06.660 --> 00:38:09.380
Are they participating in online learning?

00:38:09.380 --> 00:38:12.140
Are they in different user groups looking for mentors?

00:38:12.140 --> 00:38:15.360
Are they reading textbooks at home?

00:38:15.360 --> 00:38:16.600
I think all that's really important.

00:38:16.600 --> 00:38:26.020
And really, for people who don't have the formal education, you can see people who are doing this when they get to the technical interview and they're breaking down problems.

00:38:26.020 --> 00:38:32.800
And you get to see how they think and how they evaluate the code that they would intend to write or whatever the problem is they're trying to solve.

00:38:32.800 --> 00:38:36.620
So, in a nutshell, both are great backgrounds.

00:38:36.620 --> 00:38:44.420
But I think it's how you continue that learning for people who don't have formal education that's going to help compensate for some of the knowledge you're missing.

00:38:44.420 --> 00:38:44.620
Yeah.

00:38:44.620 --> 00:38:49.300
So, the answer is, it depends.

00:38:49.300 --> 00:38:58.640
For example, a person with a solid computer science degree could also have a solid knowledge in a particular technology stack or domain and vice versa.

00:38:58.640 --> 00:39:01.760
And definitely, I would prefer that person.

00:39:02.340 --> 00:39:06.580
But the real world situation is a little bit harder than this.

00:39:06.580 --> 00:39:15.640
And I think that currently formal education is not the number one priority in terms of making decision to hire a candidate or not.

00:39:15.640 --> 00:39:20.160
But what really matters is the experience.

00:39:20.820 --> 00:39:23.500
Experience person reduces costs for businesses.

00:39:23.500 --> 00:39:27.500
Experience lowers entry barriers.

00:39:27.500 --> 00:39:39.040
Experience also reduces the likelihood of technical debt which this person could introduce, thereby decreasing the productivity of other developers.

00:39:40.040 --> 00:39:51.780
And nowadays, the gap between people who have a formal computer science education and those people who don't have is decreasing with the introduction of MOOCs.

00:39:51.780 --> 00:39:52.880
What is MOOC?

00:39:52.880 --> 00:39:56.160
MOOC is a massive open online course.

00:39:56.520 --> 00:40:08.500
And platforms like Coursera, like Edex, like Udacity, MIT and so on, they provide tons of high quality courses free of charge.

00:40:09.040 --> 00:40:19.860
And I think that we are living a very, very special life where education is becoming cheap and affordable for everybody with the access to the internet.

00:40:19.860 --> 00:40:26.660
So, you can go there and start learning something new with thousands of students.

00:40:26.660 --> 00:40:28.420
That's a great opportunity.

00:40:28.420 --> 00:40:32.540
You can collaborate with them and you can help each other.

00:40:34.440 --> 00:40:49.600
If I had to choose between someone with a solid degree and no experience, and someone with a couple years experience but no degree, that really wouldn't give me enough information because neither one of those things tells me how a person is going to be in my group.

00:40:49.600 --> 00:40:51.440
If they're going to be a culture fit.

00:40:51.440 --> 00:40:53.140
If they're going to continue to learn.

00:40:53.140 --> 00:40:56.440
How much they really love what they do.

00:40:56.440 --> 00:41:03.380
One question I always like to ask is, if we made you an offer and you had an identical offer from another company.

00:41:03.860 --> 00:41:04.960
Same money, same everything.

00:41:04.960 --> 00:41:06.660
Why would you choose us?

00:41:06.660 --> 00:41:12.100
I want someone who appreciates the environment of a startup and the type of people they'd be working with.

00:41:12.100 --> 00:41:13.760
The people that are interviewing them.

00:41:13.760 --> 00:41:19.240
Who talk about themselves during the interview to give them an idea of what we're like.

00:41:19.240 --> 00:41:22.080
And the main thing is a culture fit.

00:41:22.080 --> 00:41:24.220
Even if they didn't know Python.

00:41:24.960 --> 00:41:41.700
And beyond that, someone who really loves what they do, is willing to always learn, is always curious, is going to bring their ideas and things they discover out in the open source world into our company and make everyone better and make our product better.

00:41:42.420 --> 00:41:43.920
That is what I'm looking for.

00:41:43.920 --> 00:41:47.680
And the education and experience just don't matter.

00:41:49.240 --> 00:41:51.300
This last question was an optional one.

00:41:51.300 --> 00:41:53.700
I didn't want to put anybody on the spot.

00:41:53.700 --> 00:41:55.200
So I said, answer it if you want.

00:41:55.200 --> 00:41:56.640
Otherwise, just skip it.

00:41:56.640 --> 00:41:58.780
And a couple of our panelists answered it.

00:41:58.780 --> 00:42:03.000
And that question was, why did you hire the last person you hired?

00:42:03.060 --> 00:42:12.940
And I ask this because it's great to talk in theory about comparing formal education versus experience versus side projects.

00:42:12.940 --> 00:42:15.940
But actions often speak louder than words.

00:42:15.940 --> 00:42:19.460
And in this case, I thought maybe we'd find something interesting.

00:42:19.460 --> 00:42:22.620
Well, you know, that's actually kind of funny.

00:42:22.620 --> 00:42:26.620
The last person I hired was someone who was interviewing for a manager position with us.

00:42:26.620 --> 00:42:29.460
Actually, but we hired him for a position as an engineer.

00:42:30.080 --> 00:42:36.840
Because as we looked at what he was really interested in doing, he was passionate about technical innovation and was very, very strong in that area.

00:42:36.840 --> 00:42:44.820
He was interviewing for a manager position because he had been a manager before and was used to working in environments where the way you got to be technically innovative was to be a manager.

00:42:44.820 --> 00:42:51.020
Because as an IC, individual contributor, all you got to do was implement the technical decisions of your management chain.

00:42:51.020 --> 00:42:54.440
In our environment, it's actually exactly the opposite of that.

00:42:54.560 --> 00:43:01.940
So the IC position was a great fit for us and was a great fit for him and his passion and what he was actually interested in doing.

00:43:01.940 --> 00:43:05.140
And that's worked out really well for us and him so far.

00:43:06.860 --> 00:43:12.800
So I gave my most recent thumbs up to a developer who knew Django and was willing to continue working with it.

00:43:12.800 --> 00:43:17.340
But most importantly, he could start on site before the wreck closed.

00:43:17.340 --> 00:43:21.920
You see, in large companies, empty seats have expiration dates.

00:43:21.920 --> 00:43:24.020
And everyone is willing to gamble.

00:43:24.020 --> 00:43:26.700
Because somebody is better than nobody.

00:43:27.100 --> 00:43:31.920
And even if they're worse than nobody, then you still get a backfill when they leave or are pushed out.

00:43:31.920 --> 00:43:34.480
But this developer seems to be working out.

00:43:34.480 --> 00:43:37.220
And I only helped hire him for another team.

00:43:37.220 --> 00:43:38.720
So let me talk about one other one.

00:43:38.720 --> 00:43:43.300
The last engineer I hired onto my team was recruited over the course of two years.

00:43:43.300 --> 00:43:45.220
I met him at PyCon 2012.

00:43:45.220 --> 00:43:48.180
And we collaborated on a few open source projects.

00:43:48.180 --> 00:43:52.960
And, you know, eventually the planets aligned and he was able to join my team.

00:43:53.580 --> 00:43:59.020
Real recruiting can be a really long process, not the least of which is due to weird budgeting and bureaucracy.

00:43:59.020 --> 00:44:02.840
So don't get frustrated if you're still waiting on an email reply from me.

00:44:02.840 --> 00:44:08.800
And do network and meet people and go to conferences and play that long game.

00:44:08.800 --> 00:44:15.480
One last piece of advice I usually give people as well is to, if you're really just looking for a job,

00:44:15.480 --> 00:44:17.660
you want to get into the mix with the industry,

00:44:18.200 --> 00:44:23.760
Just make sure that your LinkedIn profile exists and says that you are a software engineer.

00:44:23.760 --> 00:44:29.320
And then just change your location to the Bay Area or Seattle or some other tech hub.

00:44:31.080 --> 00:44:38.420
Actually, I hired a person just recently for about two or two and a half weeks ago.

00:44:38.420 --> 00:44:46.300
This person is a young, smart guy without actually strong computer science formal education,

00:44:46.300 --> 00:44:51.760
but with some little bit of working experience.

00:44:52.520 --> 00:44:56.760
Previously, he only worked in one place as a web developer.

00:44:56.760 --> 00:45:03.700
But the thing which makes him different from others is his passion for knowledge.

00:45:03.700 --> 00:45:10.040
I was amazed by his habit of reading books on a regular basis.

00:45:10.040 --> 00:45:13.560
He explores and learns different MOOCs.

00:45:14.280 --> 00:45:21.440
We just recently took the MOOC from Coursera, which is called Learning How to Learn.

00:45:21.440 --> 00:45:24.780
I highly recommend this course to listeners.

00:45:24.780 --> 00:45:26.060
Take a look.

00:45:26.060 --> 00:45:28.160
This course is very, very good.

00:45:28.160 --> 00:45:29.780
Learning How to Learn.

00:45:29.780 --> 00:45:35.080
And he's interested not only in computer-related subjects,

00:45:35.080 --> 00:45:39.880
but, you know, other stuff like scientific, non-fiction, and so on.

00:45:40.460 --> 00:45:44.720
And also, he reads tons of code from different open source projects

00:45:44.720 --> 00:45:47.180
and making some contributions to them.

00:45:47.180 --> 00:45:52.100
Because I think that because of technology is a rapidly growing area,

00:45:52.100 --> 00:45:56.520
everybody should stay hungry and be curious.

00:45:56.520 --> 00:46:00.160
Because we are lucky enough to be a part of something

00:46:00.160 --> 00:46:03.100
which can change people's lives in a better way.

00:46:03.100 --> 00:46:09.100
And the idea of creating something that can be used by millions of people is fascinating.

00:46:09.880 --> 00:46:14.440
And people who are fascinated are willing to continuously improve themselves.

00:46:14.440 --> 00:46:21.580
And I wish everybody to be fascinated and improve their life and themselves in a better way.

00:46:21.580 --> 00:46:23.200
Thank you very much.

00:46:24.480 --> 00:46:28.080
Rather than discuss why I hired any individual,

00:46:28.080 --> 00:46:32.800
I'd rather talk about why I've hired my favorite people that I've hired.

00:46:32.800 --> 00:46:36.760
And there are many recurring reasons.

00:46:36.760 --> 00:46:39.520
And among them are they're interested in open source.

00:46:39.520 --> 00:46:44.260
They're interested in the community that brings us the tools that we use every day.

00:46:44.860 --> 00:46:47.180
They keep themselves up to date.

00:46:47.180 --> 00:46:49.520
They follow key people on Twitter.

00:46:49.520 --> 00:46:50.680
They're on mailing lists.

00:46:50.680 --> 00:46:51.560
They go to conferences.

00:46:51.560 --> 00:46:52.720
They follow blogs.

00:46:52.720 --> 00:46:56.200
They're interested in doing things the right way.

00:46:56.200 --> 00:46:58.360
They follow the community's best practices.

00:46:58.360 --> 00:46:59.260
They use linters.

00:46:59.500 --> 00:47:04.260
They pay attention to style because it doesn't matter to a certain extent.

00:47:04.780 --> 00:47:08.140
If the code works, it matters that I have to be able to read it.

00:47:08.140 --> 00:47:09.440
I have to be able to maintain it.

00:47:09.440 --> 00:47:16.700
Maintainability is by far the number one most important thing in programming, in my opinion.

00:47:17.520 --> 00:47:25.800
And someone who's not satisfied with meeting the requirements, someone who wants to make it better, they want to do it the right way.

00:47:25.800 --> 00:47:36.360
And I don't mean an ivory tower, unattainable perfection that it has to be done exactly textbook perfectly.

00:47:36.360 --> 00:47:41.500
Just it's done well enough that it's easy to maintain.

00:47:41.500 --> 00:47:43.160
It's easy for other people to understand.

00:47:43.160 --> 00:47:45.680
They're not taking egregious shortcuts.

00:47:46.440 --> 00:47:48.640
They leave the code better than they found it.

00:47:48.640 --> 00:47:57.400
And they're someone whose code review you want to do and someone you want to talk to at lunch about code and just generally hang out with.

00:47:57.400 --> 00:48:00.940
Well, that's it for the questions.

